    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i've heard some people say you gotta be careful with the corners though. what's the deal with the inside corners/joints? they seem to show imperfections way easier than the flat walls.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Inside corners require a slightly different approach because the angles concentrate stress where mud is often thinner. Start by applying a perimeter bead of mud directly along the corner before applying tape, which helps build up the initial core. Use a wider application of compound initially and feather the edges out extensively into the corner transitions to disguise the structural change.",
      "source": "target",
